At first we did not know what to do with the bodies. We placed them in the front rooms of our houses, waiting for them to be taken away. But nobody came. And the dead kept piling up.

It was then that we decided to bury our dead. But we were all afraid. We had never seen such a thing before. When we touched the dead bodies we felt cold, like ice. We washed them, put on their shrouds, carried them on stretchers and buried them.

But the bodies did not decompose. They remained as if they were alive. The limbs did not stiffen. The eyes were not clouded over. The skin did not turn blue or black.

At first we were horrified. We thought that the dead were being punished. We believed that they had not died properly. We did not know what to do. We were afraid to go near them.

The bodies did not rot for many months. They became harder and harder. They were like logs of wood. We were terrified to touch them. They became our own dead. We could not bear to look at them.

I have a lot of favorite stories about visits from spirits, but this one really stands out. I like this story because of the comfort and reassurance I got from the ghost of my grandmother.

I was about 8 years old. It was a very cold night and I had been crying. My grandmother had died a few months before, and I missed her very much. I was really missing her that night. I was crying and my mother was upset. She had tried to comfort me, but I was inconsolable. She put me to bed, but I was still crying and asking to go downstairs.

I was in bed, crying, when I heard the front door open. I looked out of my bedroom window and saw my grandmother walking up the path to the house. I saw her, plain as day, in a long coat, coming up the path. I heard the door open and close again. She came into the bedroom and stood beside my bed. She didn't say anything, but she was smiling. I smiled back, and felt so happy and at peace. She just stood there for a while, then she walked out of the room.

I lay in bed, and I was no longer crying. I was calm, and I felt so happy and peaceful. I don't know how long she stayed, but I remember lying there, thinking about how happy I was. I knew she was there for me. I knew she was there to help me, and that she would always be there. I fell asleep, feeling so much better.

This is my favorite story, because it happened to me, and it made me feel better. It made me feel happy and loved.

This is a story about a visit from a spirit that came to visit me when I was young. I had been feeling a bit lonely, and I was having a hard time dealing with the fact that my grandmother had died. I was very sad and upset, and I was crying.

My grandmother was very kind and loving, and she was always there for me when I needed her. She was a great source of comfort for me. I was very close to her, and I loved her very much.

President Tsai Ing-wen () has made repeated promises to prioritize disaster prevention, saying in her New Year's address that the nation would spend more on improving the prevention infrastructure and improve its responsiveness to disasters.

However, even the simplest changes  like putting warning signs on areas that are at high risk for landslides  have not been implemented, despite the repeated recommendations of experts, Democratic Progressive Party (DPP) Legislator Tuan Yi-kang () said.

Tuan, who is also the DPP caucus whip, said he had proposed a motion to improve the safety of roads in mountainous areas"We need to look at whether we have the appropriate technology to assess the safety of roads and buildings in areas that are prone to landslides and rockfalls," he said.

In addition to implementing the proper infrastructure, Tuan said, the government must communicate with the public.

"You cannot just tell the public to stay away from areas that are prone to landslides. They have to know where those areas are, and they need to be able to make an informed decision," he said.

Landslides and mudslides are expected to increase during the spring due to the arrival of the northeast monsoon and typhoons.

Landslides are the main cause of deaths during typhoons, and the nation is expecting a busy typhoon season this year, according to the Central Weather Bureau.

It is likely that there will be between six and nine typhoons, with at least three or four directly hitting the nation, bureau Director-General Chung San-cheng () said on Tuesday.

Heavy rainfall is expected during the typhoon season, which runs from April to October, and the average precipitation in the first four months of the year is the highest it has been in the past 10 years, Chung said.

The highest average precipitation in the first four months of the year was recorded in 2009, when it reached 1,227.9mm, he said.

The rain is expected to continue for the next two weeks, he said, adding that the water levels in the nation's reservoirs are high and the soil in mountainous areas is sat which means that there is an increased risk of landslides.

A series of strong earthquakes that struck the nation last year  including the Hualien earthquake in February and the Tainan earthquake in March  has also weakened the structural integrity of buildings and roads, he said.

Citing the example of the Hualien earthquake, the bureau said that there were reports of damage to a bridge and the railway, which was caused by landslides.

The bureau said that the potential for a disaster is high this year, and it urged people to keep abreast of weather warnings and disaster information.

The agency is to take over the responsibility of issuing disaster information from the National Fire Agency.

The change in policy is to help the agency prepare for the possibility of a disaster in the future, bureau Deputy Director-General Cheng Ming-dean () said.

I felt fuming when I saw the flyer, I called up the school right away and confronted the principal, saying "How could you do that?" She told me, "Well, it's our mascot." I said, "Well, we don't have mascots. We don't have anything that represents animals or animal parts or animal testing." She said, "Well, our mascot is a lion, and we think it's OK." And I said, "You don't think it's OK, because you have not been educated. You need to read about the facts." She said, "Well, you can give us a presentation, and if you do a good job, we'll change our mascot." I said, "Yes, of course. I will do it." I brought some information about the suffering of animals in labs. She invited me to present it to the students. I told the kids what I knew about animals in labs, and the kids were horrified. They were crying. They were really upset.

I asked the kids, "If you don't want to see animals suffering, then why do you have a lion as your mascot?" They said, "We have no choice. We have to have it." I told them, "You don't have to have it. You can change it. You can be the ones to do it. You have the power to change it." I went back to the principal and said, "You know, if the kids are so against it, then they're not going to be happy with the lion as a mascot. Why don't we change it?" And she said, "Yes, you're right. You can change it."

The kids were so happy and so proud of themselves. We went on to the board of education. The principal asked me to speak to the board, and I did. They agreed with us. They agreed that the mascot was offensive. They agreed to change the mascot. They agreed to teach kids about animal rights in the school. I was so proud of the kids and of the board of education. They made history that day. It was the first school in Canada to change its mascot to one that didn't promote the use of animals. It was really an amazing victory.

I started doing some other work with kids. I went to other schools, and I got involved in Kids Against Animal Testing. We did some projects and did some fundraising for the American Anti-Vivisection Society. We raised a lot of money for them, and I got to know the people at the organization. They were so nice and so good. They were like my mentors. They taught me so much. They inspired me. They encouraged me to keep going. They believed in me. They believed that I could make a difference. They taught me so much about how to be an activist and how to get the message out.

We worked on some other projects. We had a very successful campaign to stop pigeon shooting in Toronto. We also worked on a campaign to stop a fur shop in Toronto. We did a lot of campaigning in schools. We did some public speaking. We did some leafleting. We did some lobbying. We did a lot of work with the media. I was interviewed by the media a lot. I returned to my seat. As the meeting went on, I looked over at Mabel and Javier several times. He was such a beautiful baby, and I wondered how I would ever have time to be a mother.

_I'm not ready to have a baby_ , I thought. _I have so much I want to do_.

I still wanted to go to law school, and I wasn't even sure if I wanted to marry Juan. But the more I saw Mabel and her baby, the more I wondered if I might be ready for motherhood after all.

### CHAPTER FOUR

### Coming Home

IN EARLY 1975, I DIDN'T KNOW WHETHER I WOULD EVER see my family again. After the assassination of the Chilean president, General Augusto Pinochet had banned all political activity and begun to repress and terrorize the Chilean people. People like my father, who had been politically active, were under constant surveillance. They were tortured, and some were murdered. My family, along with other political refugees, was banned from entering Chile. I would not see my mother, my sisters, or my brother until the Pinochet regime fell, almost eleven years later.

I felt safe in the United States, but I missed my family terribly. I had tried to remain optimistic, but in my heart, I knew that my mother and my sisters had been arrested. I also knew that my father, who was on the run, was no longer alive. My family's history of political activism, the fact that we were living in a foreign country, and my own political involvement had made me a target. I was not only being punished for my family's past actions; I was being punished for my own. I knew I had to get out of Chile.

I tried to go back to college in 1974, but I couldn't focus on my studies. My heart was in Chile, and I could think of nothing but getting back to my family.

I called the university and told them I was withdrawing from school. I asked for an academic leave of absence. They agreed, but I was afraid they might change their minds. I knew I had to leave the country as soon as possible.

One way to encourage someone is to give them a compliment. This does not mean that you have to say something false. You can find something that is true about the person you are encouraging, and say it to them. For example, you can say, "I like the way you play soccer. You really run fast."

Another way to encourage someone is to be specific. For example, you can say, "I like the way you can catch the ball."

Another way to encourage someone is to offer your help. For example, you can say, "I will help you study for your next test."

If you are not sure what to say, you can pray and ask God to give you the right words. God loves to help us when we need encouragement.

In the Bible, Paul wrote that we are to "encourage one another." (1 Thessalonians 5:11) When we encourage one another, we build each other up. And, when we encourage one another, we are obeying God.

God has encouraged us by giving us His Word, the Bible. And He encourages us when we ask Him for help.

God is always ready to encourage us. He knows when we are discouraged, and He knows just what to say to us.

Remember, too, that when we encourage someone else, we are being like Jesus. Jesus is the best encourager of all!

The Bible says that we are to "encourage one another." (1 Thessalonians 5:11) One way to do this is to give someone a compliment.

The word "compliment" means "praise." When you compliment someone, you are saying something nice to them. A compliment is a positive thing that you say to someone else.

There are many ways to give someone a compliment. Here are some examples. (Use your own words, and think about your friend.)

1. You did a great job on that test!
2. That's a pretty shirt!
3. You play soccer really well.
4. You have a nice smile.
5. Your hair looks really nice.
6. You did a great job washing the car.

When you give someone a compliment, you are saying something nice to them. But, you are also saying something good about yourself. You are saying that you have good thoughts about other people. And that is what God wants you to do.

God loves to give us compliments. He tells us that we are His children. He tells us that we are forgiven. He tells us that He loves us. He tells us that He has a good plan for our lives. He tells us that He will take care of us. He tells us that He will never leave us.

When you compliment someone, you are doing something that God does. You are telling someone that they are special to you. And, you are telling them that they are special to God.

Another way to encourage someone is to offer your help. For example, you can say, "I will help you study for your next test."

Shen's interest in the natural world led her to study the environment in college. She received a Bachelor of Arts in environmental studies from Brown University and a Master of Science in environmental science from the University of Michigan.

But it was while working at the Georgia Conservancy in Atlanta that she began to paint. "I was doing environmental policy work, and I was going to be doing that for a long time. I realized that what I really wanted to do was art," she says.

She decided to enroll in art classes at night and eventually decided to move to New York City to earn a master's degree in fine arts from the School of Visual Arts.

While Shen loves to paint, she says her experience as an environmental scientist still influences her work.

"My work is a combination of all my passions," she says. "The environment is my primary passion, and I can't not think about it in my work. I'm always thinking about how we treat the environment and how we can improve our treatment of the environment.

"I'm always thinking about how we treat the environment and how we can improve our treatment of the environment."

"My paintings are a form of activism. I want to inspire people to care about the environment. I want to get people to think about what we're doing to the planet."
